dditional option of uploading the document from your computer or using a URL.\r\n4. When you have included the work or URL or file that you want to check, you will then click on the button that signifies “check plagiarism” and give the tool some seconds to run the check\r\n5. The result of the check will be shown and it will display whether the work is completely free of plagiarism or whether some parts of the work is plagiarized\r\n6. You have the option of rewriting the plagiarized parts and checking it again to be sure\r\n \r\nIS PLAGIARISMCHECKER.EU A GOOD PLAGIARISM CHECKER?\r\nPlagiarismchecker.eu is one of the numerous plagiarism checker tools that can be used to check if a paper or document is free of plagiarism. This particular plagiarism tool has over time stood to be a good and reliable plagiarism check tool because of its speed and efficiency.\r\nPlagiarismchecker.eu amongst its many uniqueness also ensures the safety of your paper  by automatically deleting  every uploaded documents after 24hrs, except you opt to save the document. Also, your work is not added to comparative databases just to avoid any possibility of leak.\r\nPlagiarismchecker.eu is also very quick and accurate, which makes it a good plagiarism check tool. The time it takes for a document to be checked is 0.75 minutes  for an average of  a 20 page document and consists of 10% plagiarism. Moreover, it guarantees to give 98% accuracy if a work is plagiarized.\r\nPlagiarismchecker.eu is made to suit the needs of varying range of individuals from students, teachers, writers, bloggers, and many more, all customized with different functions and uses to solve different problems. Its large comparative database  makes it outstanding. Plagiarismchecker.eu boasts of over 70 databases and well over 3 million sources are available to be compared with your work.\r\n \r\nWHAT ARE THE FOUR TYPES OF PLAGIARISM?\r\nPlagiarism comes in different ways and forms, and should be avoided by all means because of the serious consequences it poses. There are different types of plagiarism but we will focus on the four major types of plagiarism:\r\n1. Direct Plagiarism:  This occurs when you copy a part of someone’s work in its totality and use it for your work without giving the copied work the proper citation. Here the exact same words are used without citing the source of the information. This is the worst kind of plagiarism and should be avoided. This is why it is important to run your work through a plagiarism checker before submitting.\r\n2. Self plagiarism: Self plagiarism is when someone copies their previously  submitted work without the permission of persons involved in that work. It is most frequent in students turning in a work already done by them without the permission of professors involved in that work.\r\n3. Accidental Plagiarism: Here, the plagiarism is not intended but it still carries the same consequences. It happens when someone unintentionally or neglects to quote the source of the information they used  or uses the same kind of words and phrases without proper citation. A good plagiarism checker can be used to identify any plagiarized content in your work for proper citation.\r\n4. Source based plagiarism: This can occur in different ways. It can be as a result of citing a wrong or non existent source  or when all the sources used for a work are not entirely captured in the references given in the work. It can also come in the form of data fabrication.\r\n \r\nCAN YOU GO TO JAIL FOR PLAGIARISM?\r\nPlagiarism is quite a big deal and should be taken seriously because it is a crime with punishment ranging from fine to jail terms. There are legal consequences of plagiarizing a work, as it falls into certain aspects of copyright laws and is a breach. This is why there are tons of plagiarism checker tool out there to enable you detect if your work has some plagiarized contents and to correct immediately.\r\nMost times plagiarism is considered as a misdemeanor, which is punishable by fine. The amount to be fined varies from country to country in line with the law governing such offense, and in some cases, it can earn you a jail term up to one year. In some countries, plagiarism is considered to be a felony under some federal and state laws, and one can face up to ten years jail time; for example if the person that plagiarized another persons work earn more money than the original owner of  the work. With such consequences, it is advisable to make use of the plenty available plagiarism check tools to avoid being fined or even going to jail because of plagiarism.\r\n \r\nWHAT PERCENTAGE OF PLAGIARISM IS ACCEPTABLE?\r\nGenerally plagiarism is completely not allowed and is prohibited, more so as it is not just a civil offense but also considered a criminal offense which can earn you punishments of fine or jail terms.  This is why there is so much emphasis on running your work through a plagiarism scanner to ensure that it is completely safe from any form of plagiarism.\r\nNot withstanding the above, sometimes it difficult to get a 100% free of plagiarism work, which is why some certain percentage of plagiarism is allowed. There are however   no consensus on the amount of plagiarism that can be accepted or overlooked in a manuscript or paper. By popular practices one can say anything below 5% is acceptable,  between 5 to 10 % is not very bad and can be overlooked but if it above 15% then there is a call for concern and that paper should be looked into as it will be deemed to be highly plagiarized. Even in the 15% that is acceptable,  if it is totally from a particular material, then it might be considered as being a plagiarized work . To be on the safe side,  a good plagiarism scanner can be used to reduce traces of plagiarism to the barest minimum.\r\n \r\nWHAT PERCENTAGE OF SIMILARITY IS ACCEPTABLE?\r\nFirst, it is instructive to state that plagiarism and similarity are both different things and shouldn&apos;t be confused with each other.  Plagiarism involves copying some one&apos;s work without giving them the credit by quotation or citation, while similarity includes common word, terms and phrases that might be found in a particular work.\r\nJust like plagiarism, there is no consensus on the acceptable rate of similarity to be allowed in a work, however most opinions are that it is more difficult to avoid similarity than it is to avoid plagiarism. It is almost impossible to completely avoid similar words and phrases especially where such words are popular online. Most persons have pegged the acceptable similarity at 20 to 25 % however the lesser the similarity, the better and more accurate your work will be.  To detect similarity in your work, use a plagiarism scanner to check the work before submitting. The plagiarism checker will indicate how many percent of your work is either plagiarized or similar in text to other works, thereby giving you the opportunity to correct . To avoid incidences of similarity, try to paraphrase your work as much as you can to reduce the chances of similarity.\r\n \r\nWHAT ARE THE 10 TYPES OF PLAGIARISM?\r\nPlagiarism is a popular syndrome for persons that interact with a lot of writing examples, including teachers, students, professors and so on. There are different types of plagiarism and a plagiarism scanner can be used to detect most of them. However, we will be looking at 10 most common types of plagiarism:\r\n1. Clone plagiarism : This is most popular and perhaps the worst kind of plagiarism. Here, there is a verbatim replication of someone&apos;s work with little or no changes, and no proper citation and reference is given to the work copied .\r\n2 . Error plagiarism (404 error): This occurs where someone quotes an incorrect or non existent source as their references. It is usually impossible to trace such citations because it will lead to non existing sources.\r\n3. Self plagiarism : This type of plagiarism is also common. It happens when someone copies their former work without giving it proper citation.\r\n4. Hybrid plagiarism : Here, information is copied from well cited sources but no reference is given to all the information copied. The writer now presents the copied work as a new one.\r\n5. Find and replace plagiarism : The trick here is to make changes in the  major  keywords and phrases with closely related words, without necessarily changing the whole idea in the context.\r\n6. Remix plagiarism : This kind of plagiarism occurs where a writer copies ideas from different places and puts them all together in a way that is fit and understandable, then claims the work to be his own idea.\r\n7. Aggregator plagiarism : Here, the writer includes the correct references and citations of where he got ideas from, but the problem with this is that the work is almost made up of someone else&apos;s idea and lacks originality.\r\n8. Mashup plagiarism : This type of plagiarism occurs when the writer copies information from lots of sources, joins them together in his own document without properly citing or referencing the various sources.\r\n9. Data falsification : When a writer tampers with the data obtained from another source with the intention of misleading the public, then it is plagiarism. Any such alteration should be duly notified to the appropriate authorities.\r\n10. Inaccurate authorship: Here, a person that contributed to the success of a work does not get credit for work done, or in some instances, a person that did not contribute to the work gets credit for it.\r\nAll these incidences of plagiarism can be reasonably avoided if the work is checked through a plagiarism scanner.\r\n \r\n \r\nWHAT IS AN EXAMPLE OF PLAGIARISM?\r\nPlagiarism is very popular amongst academicians, writers and journalists. Basically, it means copying someone&apos;s idea or work without giving them credit for the work by citing or referencing them . There are different forms of plagiarism and it ranges from direct plagiarism, to self plagiarism, accidental plagiarism, and so on. To avoid being caught in the likely trap of plagiarism, one should use a plagiarism checker to scan work before final submission.\r\nAn example of plagiarism could be a typical case of a student that is given a project or thesis to write . If that student fabricates or falsifies facts in his work, then he is guilty of plagiarism. Also, where the student takes hint from other sources without giving them proper reference  then it is also plagiarism. A good plagiarism checker can help you avoid that.\r\nThere are cases of popular authors that have been forced to quit and had their careers ruined because of incidences of plagiarism. Plagiarism is also not limited to writing. There are example of people who gave speeches that were deemed to be plagiarized . An example being the popular speech on social inequality and access to education for every social group, given by Joe Biden, the 47th President of the United States of America .\r\n \r\n \r\n\r\n', 'file', 0, 0, 0, '2019-10-15 23:38:17', '2019-10-15 23:38:27'),
(54, 'J6s6Pa2i31lBjV6YFs8fsk5ySth6a9', 'a@outlook.com', 'Definitions of Plagiarism.docx', '\nDefinitions of Plagiarism\r\nSo, what exactly is plagiarism?\r\nWikipedia defines plagiarism as the &apos;wrongful appropriation&apos; and &apos;stealing and publication&apos; of another author&apos;s &apos;language, thoughts, ideas, or expressions&apos; and the representation of them as one&apos;s own original work.&quot; This means that plagiarism can be seen as using someone else&apos;s original idea or material without explicitly crediting them as the authentic owner.\r\nSimilarly, according to the renowned Merriam-Webster dictionary, to plagiarize means &quot;to steal and pass off (the ideas or words of another person) as one&apos;s own or to use (another&apos;s production) without crediting the source.&quot; Simply put, plagiarism is a fraudulent act, which involves stealing someone else&apos;s work and passing it off as your own.\r\nJust like original inventions are usually patented, original ideas, also called intellectual properties, are often protected by copyright laws, which grant the exclusive rights to publish and replicate such works to the respective copyright holders.\r\nIn the same vein, Dictionary.com defines plagiarism as &quot;an act or instance of using or closely imitating the language and thoughts of another author without authorization and the representation of that author&apos;s work as one&apos;s own, as by not crediting the original author.&quot; This also implies that imitation and theft of another author&apos;s thoughts, ideas and statements without proper referencing and citation amounts to plagiarism.\r\nOther instances of plagiarism include copying someone else&apos;s work word-for-word – also called lifting, failing to enclose an excerpt in quotation marks, giving false information about the source of a quotation or copying so many words or statements from a particular source, such that it forms the majority of your own work, whether you cite the source or not. Quite simply, every one that intends to write must firstly learn how to summarize, include his ideas, and write in his own words, after thorough reading and researching for a written work. \r\nFurthermore, several other acts that amount to plagiarism include using a still image, motion picture or piece of music in a work you have produced without receiving proper authorization from the original author or content owner, or refusal to appropriately credit the author. “Plagiarism often covers things that are not covered by copyright – ideas, facts and general plot elements are all things that can be plagiarized, at least in certain situations, but generally don’t qualify for copyright protection” (Bailey, 2013).\r\nExperts advise that the best alternative to avoid plagiarism is getting adequate research knowledge and the mastery of effective writing skills. To avoid plagiarism, one must ensure the full reference details of every source used is written in one’s notes while reading and researching for a written work. It is important for writers to learn how to paraphrase, quote, and to properly cite and reference cited materials.\r\n\r\n BIBLIOGRAPHY Works Cited\r\nBailey, J. (2013). The Difference Between Copyright Infringement and Plagiarism.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'file', 0, 0, 0, '2019-10-15 23:38:57', '2019-10-15 23:39:07'),
