(56, 'C4RFpuX5MPXGYRfpQdpGNjJDJRO8M0', 'a@outlook.com', 'Plagiarism Checker for Businesses.docx', '\nPlagiarism Checker for Businesses\r\nSimply put, a plagiarism checker is software which is primarily used to detect the occurrence of plagiarized content in a material and to also track the original source of such content.\r\nIn the business sphere, it has also become important to check for plagiarism in submitted contents to guarantee originality. Hence, manuscripts, articles, essays or blog posts submitted for publishing need to be adequately crosschecked to avoid plagiarism and copyright infringement. It is no longer news that your business image can be severely marred by plagiarism should your website be found to publish duplicate contents.  \r\nGoogle defines plagiarism as the publication of duplicate content, and they have strict measures against websites found guilty of plagiarizing. If your website is found to publish too much of someone else&apos;s content, Google penalizes your website by dropping your site&apos;s URL on search results for your industry keywords. Some popular bloggers and writers have been dropped in Google search ranking because of plagiarism. \r\nNo company wants to invest its time, money and other valuable resources in attaining high ranking in SEO campaigns and then have it dropped down the rank due to claims of plagiarism. This means that the importance of hiring content creators who are reputable, well aware of writing ethics and familiar with the importance of content originality cannot be overemphasized. \r\nWhile preparing documents and other media posts for public usage, website owners, law firms and other business owners need not to only check for the accuracy of the facts presented in these documents but should also take enough time and employ the use of different plagiarism checking software and web applications available today to track the occurrence of plagiarism in submitted contents in a bid to avoid being sanctioned for publishing plagiarized materials. It may initially seem elusive to always avoid plagiarism, especially for start-up businesses without a member with writing expertise. Businesses like this find it difficult to develop their own views, and end up paraphrasing any work they love in a bid to assimilate their arguments. Nonetheless, it is crucial for every business to develop their own voice and become an independent original thinker. If a business is not careful, just what would have been a simple plagiarism can turn out to be copyright infringement, and induce litigation. “Whereas attribution can negate the act of plagiarism, it does not mitigate copyright infringement which can occur whether or not the author of a work has been properly identified” (Fishman, 2009).\r\nEven though manual checks for plagiarism often take time, automated plagiarism checkers available online are usually faster and can accurately highlight plagiarized contents, so they can be promptly corrected. The time it takes to review a submitted piece for plagiarism will eventually be worth it when the originality of your articles and posts can be verified.\r\nWorks Cited\r\n BIBLIOGRAPHY Fishman, T. (2009). &quot;We know it when we see it&quot; is not good enough: toward a standard definition of plagiarism that transcends theft, fraud, and copyright.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'file', 1, 0, 0, '2019-10-15 23:40:17', '2019-10-15 23:40:30'),
(57, 'yxHGyhN5fpNUjNWFWhmPU7COhHtDRk', 'a@outlook.com', 'plagiarism checker for universities.docx', '\nPlagiarism Checker for Universities\r\nTertiary institutions like universities and colleges need an efficient plagiarism checking system put in place, so as to ensure that journals, dissertations, thesis, term papers and research articles submitted by students, lecturers and researchers are qualitative and original. This is to forestall any issues that might arise as a consequence of infringing copyright and authorship laws, and also to ascertain the integrity of a submitted document and prevent theft of intellectual property. Students that are aware that their universities make use of a plagiarism checker to review their works often personally check their works for plagiarism before submitting, which may not be advisable, especially using free plagiarism checkers online. This is because some websites lure people by claiming to offer free plagiarism checks, but end up selling students’ assignments to other students. In situations like this, the student’s assignment will show up as stolen or plagiarized after submission and review. According to Sidney Kawimbe, students now prefer outsourcing their coursework and assignments, and it is the current academic system and its members that lose in this case, rather than the students or the hired writers. He has this to say: “the ideals that they hold regarding ethics, integrity and academic honors are thrown out the window” (Kawimbe, 2017).\r\nFor a university plagiarism checking tool to be effective and productive, it must be as user-friendly as possible without compromising throughput and speed. Some of the important features of a working university plagiarism checking tool include:\r\nAdd/Remove Users: This feature allows new users to register and be added to the plagiarism checking tool. Old users can log in and use the system while new users can create new account profiles. While this is not an important feature for a personal account on a plagiarism checking system, the system administrator uses this functionality to manage the registration of the end users and authentication of account details, bearing in mind that privileges differ between students&apos; and teachers&apos; accounts on the system.\r\nAssign Submissions: When students submit their documents for plagiarism check on the system, these submissions are assigned to be reviewed by the teachers by a predefined algorithm. This means that the submitted documents are usually assigned to each teacher at the discretion of the system administrator of the university or faculty. For example, a total of 1000 submitted documents to be reviewed for plagiarism might be distributed evenly amongst the 10 registered teachers on the university&apos;s plagiarism checking system or depending on another basis.\r\nStatus of Submission: This feature is exclusive to the teacher&apos;s account as it allows the teacher to see what documents have been assigned to him/her to review, and displays a pop-up message if there are new files assigned for plagiarism check.\r\nAccount Privileges: As stated earlier, privileges of access should vary between students&apos; and teachers&apos; accounts on the university&apos;s plagiarism checking system. A student&apos;s account allows for the submission of documents and access to the final report of the plagiarism review but does not grant permission to review the document for plagiarism which is an exclusive privilege for the teacher account.\r\nStatistics of Usage: This gives an overall metrics of how users frequently use the university plagiarism checking system, such as total number of submissions, percentage of submitted document reviewed, etc.\r\nWorks Cited\r\n BIBLIOGRAPHY Kawimbe, S. (2017). The new plagiarism in colleges and universities.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n', 'file', 1, 0, 0, '2019-10-16 01:37:01', '2019-10-16 01:37:03'),
